Student Grade Analysis

May 18, 2020

Sharmaine Cameron, Ian Krasnansky, Sonya Radichkova

Introduction

Guiding Question: How do external factors (such as internet access, parents education level, parents relationship status, family size, etc) impact a students grades in secondary education?

Receiving a quality education can be a crucial component to living a fruitful and successful life. Individuals who were high achieving students, which suggests they got the most out of their education, have an easier time finding jobs, benefit from developing professional relationships in school, have improved written and oral communication skills, are more independent, and substantially improve the lives of their future children among other advantages. However, not everyones educational experience is the same. Educational experiences can vary greatly as a result of uncontrollable life factors. In this Data Science tutorial, we will explore the impact various life factors may or may not have an impact on a students academic performance. # Data Preparation

The first step of any data science project is to either collect data or find a dataset to use. Here, we are using a dataset titled Student Alcohol Consumption, avalable at https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption/data. This dataset contains survey results and grade statistics from secondary school students.

After downloading student-mat.csv, we can import the data and check it out with the following code.

We can immediately see that there are quite a lot of statistics beyond just alchohol consumption here. Before proceeding, we will pick a subset of these for use in our analysis. Ive picked age, famsize, Pstatus, Medu, Fedu, traveltime, studytime, activities, higher, internet, romantic, and of course the grade stats G1, G2, and G3.

Attribute List
  1. age: Students age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  2. famsize: Family size (binary: LE3 - less or equal to 3 or GT3 - greater than 3)
  3. Pstatus: Parents cohabitation status (binary: T - living together or A - living apart)
  4. Medu: Mothers education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary
  5. Fedu: Fathers education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary
  6. traveltime: Home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
  7. studytime: Weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  8. activities: Extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
  9. higher: Wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
  10. internet: Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
  11. romantic: With a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  12. G1: First trimester grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  13. G2: Second trimester grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  14. G3: Third trimester grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)

If you are confused as to what these attributes represent, remember that you can see a full explanation at https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption/data. Below is the code for removing the attributes we wont be using (or more accurately, selecting the attributes we will be using).

EDA

EDA, short for exploratory data analysis, is the process by which data scientists get a feel for trends within datasets. EDA allows you to understand how different variables are related. In this project, we are interested in determining which factors have the largest impact on a students average grade. In order to determine this, were going to graph each attribute against averagegrade, starting with age. Each graph takes the average of students averagegrade statistic based on another attribute.

age <- mydata %>%
  group_by(age) %>%
  summarize(Mean_Average_Grade = mean(averagegrade)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=age, y=Mean_Average_Grade)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "Age",
         y = "Average Grade") +
    ggtitle("Age vs Grade")
age

This graph groups students by their age and determines the mean grade rating for each group. There is a steady decline in average grade as age increases, besides an outlier at 20. Considering that this is a small dataset, this is to be expected. Lets continue down the line and look at famsize.

fs <- mydata %>%

Correlation Matrix

After going through the procedures of EDA, we would like to perform another type of analysis to gain a better understanding of how each attribute is related to other attributes and how each attribute is related to averagegrades. To do this we will use a Correlation Matrix. A Correlation Matrix displays the correlation between attributes using coefficients. The coefficients take on values between negative one and positive one. Coefficient values that are closer to positive one represent a perfect positive relationship while coefficient values that are closer to negative one are representative of a perfect negative relationship. Coefficient values near zero correspond to attributes that are the least correlated.

Our correlation matrix shows that no attribute is particularly correlated with averagegrades. Most of the coefficient values are near zero and none of them surpass 0.5 or go below -0.5, but there are a few that come close. The attributes with the most negative correspondence to averagegrade according to the correlation matrix are age, traveltime, and romantic. This allows us to assume that a student who is older or lives farther from school or is in a romantic relationship are slightly more likely to have lower grades than if the student is younger or lived closer to school or is not in a romantic relationship. The attributes with the most positive correspondence to averagegrade according to the correlation matrix are Medu, higher, and Fedu. This suggests that a student whose parents reached higher levels of education or a student who intends to reach higher levels of education is slightly more likely to have higher grades than others. Interestingly, the correlation matrix also shows mothers education is highly positively correlated with fathers education suggesting that if a students mother reached higher levels of education it is very likely their father also did too and vice versa. For more information about correlation matrices and their uses, visit https://www.displayr.com/what-is-a-correlation-matrix/.

numeric.var = sapply(mydata, as.numeric)
corr.matrix = cor(numeric.var)
plot_correlation(corr.matrix)

Linear Regression

We will be using linear regression in order to conduct hypothesis testing. We chose linear regression instead of logistic regression since averagegrade is a continuous numeric attribute rather than a binary value of 0 or 1. Our null hypothesis is that none of the factors have an impact on student grades. We will be using linear regression to predict the possible outcome for average grades among students with a rejection threshold of 0.05. Looking at the table below in the estimate column, for parents education, especially the mothers, we see that students average grades increase by around one point the higher the education of the parent. We test to see if we accept or reject our null hypothesis by comparing the p value column to our rejection threshold. In doing so, we see that all factors have P values greater than the rejection threshold except for activities, studytime, higher, and romantic. This implies that activities, studytime, higher, and romantic are statistically significant, allowing us to reject the null hypothesis that none of the factors have an impact on student grades. For more information on the implementation and interpretation of linear regression models, visit https://machinelearningmastery.com/linear-regression-for-machine-learning/.

library(broom)
glm.mod = lm(averagegrade ~ age  + factor(famsize) + factor(Medu) +factor(Fedu) + traveltime +
                studytime + factor(activities) + factor(higher) +
                factor(internet) + factor(romantic), data = mydata)
tidy(glm.mod)

Random Forest

For the predictions, were using a commonly known method as the Random Forest Method. It takes the average from multiple decision trees (which vary in depth) after resampling the training data at random. Because of the randomness of these trees and how resampling takes place multiple times, this helps ensure more accurate predictions. For more information about random forest classification, visit https://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~breiman/RandomForests/cc_home.htm.

We take our data and sample it, splitting it 60/40 and placing those parts in our training and test sets, respectively. We then create a forest of 1000 trees. According to the graph, by the time weve passed 200 trees, the rate of error stays roughly the same, if not slightly decreasing.

library(randomForest)
set.seed(1234)
train_index <- sample(nrow(mydata), .6*nrow(mydata), replace = TRUE)
train_set <- mydata[train_index,]
test_set <- mydata[-train_index,]

attribute_cols <- names(mydata)
attributes <- names(mydata)
attributes <- attributes[!attributes %in% c("averagegrade")]
attributes1 <- paste(attributes, collapse = "+") #saves the column names separated by +
formula_rf <- as.formula(paste("averagegrade", attributes1, sep = " ~ "))

Random_Forest<- randomForest(formula_rf, ntree=1000, importance=TRUE, data=train_set)

plot(Random_Forest)

After plotting the Random Forest graph we use the importance function in order to see which attribute is the most important in our model by measuring the total decrease in node impurity. According to the table below, parents educational levels, age, study time and travel time appear to be the most important attributes that may contribute to average grades.

importance_table<- importance(Random_Forest, type = 2)
kable(round(importance_table, digits=2))

Conclusion

Throughout this tutorial, we have shown the use of various data analysis techniques to understand the factors that most impact student academic performance. After performing EDA we hypothesized that the most significant factors were age, parental education, travel time, and time spent studying. From the results of our analyses, we see that each of these factors are potentially good predictors of average grades and our hypothesis was correct.

By determining the factors that can affect student grades, schools can use that information in order to develop methods and resources that can help alleviate the effect of negative factors such as longer travel time and increase student academic performance.
